The organism that our amino acid chains most
likely come from is the salmonella bacteria, specifically Salmonella enterica. Salmonella enterica is also known as Salmonella choleraesuis. Salmonella enterica is known for infecting animals and also a lot of our food.


One amino acid chain is:
""
Within protein BLAST, it is shown primarily to be Salmonella enterica, SPI-1 type III secretion system protein SpaO of gene SpaO.
SPI-1 type III secretion system protein SpaO's function is to work as a protein secretion for the salmonella enterica bacteria. Secretion by salmonella are often involved during the invasion of a host's cells. In www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC94988, we see that this amino acid sequence is related to Salmonella enterica Serovar Typhimurium Type III Secretion-Associated Needle Complex: a part of Salmonella enterica's proteins create a needle complex that is used to enter through the host cell's membrane.


A second amino acid chain is:
""
Within protein BLAST, it is shown primarily to be Salmonella enterica, SPI-1 type III secretion system export apparatus protein SpaS of gene spaS. Like the previous amino acid chain, SPI-1 type III secretion system export apparatus protein SpaS is related to the secretion function of the salmonella enterica bacteria.


A third amino acid chain found through Gene Finder is:
""
Within protein BLAST, it is shown primarily to be Salmonella enterica, PI-1 type III secretion system protein SpaN of gene SpaN. Like the first amino acid chain, SPI-1 type III secretion system protein SpaN is related to the secretion function of salmonella enterica bacteria.
